<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Astronomical">Astronomical<=
/h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLarge_number=
s&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: Astronomical"><=
span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span><=
/div>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Astronomy" title=3D"Astronom=
y">astronomy</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cosmology" ti=
tle=3D"Cosmology">cosmology</a> large numbers for measures of length and ti=
me are encountered. For instance, according to the prevailing <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_Bang_model" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"=
Big Bang model">Big Bang model</a>, the universe is approximately 13.8 bill=
ion years old (equivalent to <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=
=3D"7017435500000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>4.355<span style=3D"margin-left:0.=
25em;margin-right:0.15em;">=C3=97</span>10<sup>17</sup></span> seconds). Th=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Observable_universe" title=3D"Ob=
servable universe">observable universe</a> spans 93 billion <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Light-year" title=3D"Light-year">light years</a> =
(approximately <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"702688000000=
0000000=E2=99=A0"></span>8.8<span style=3D"margin-left:0.25em;margin-right:=
0.15em;">=C3=97</span>10<sup>26</sup></span> meters) and hosts around <span=
 class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"7022499999999999999=E2=99=A0"></=
span>5<span style=3D"margin-left:0.25em;margin-right:0.15em;">=C3=97</span>=
10<sup>22</sup></span> stars, organized into roughly 125 billion galaxies (=
as observed by the Hubble Space Telescope). As a rough estimate, there are =
about <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"7080100000000000000=
=E2=99=A0"></span>10<sup>80</sup></span> atoms within the observable univer=
se.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Large_numbers#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>According to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Don_Page_(phys=
icist)" title=3D"Don Page (physicist)">Don Page</a>, physicist at the Unive=
rsity of Alberta, Canada, the longest finite time that has so far been expl=
icitly calculated by any physicist is
</p>
<dl><dd><dl><dd><dl><dd><dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-el=
ement-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" s=
tyle=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" =
alttext=3D"{\displaystyle 10^{10^{10^{10^{10^{1.1}}}}}{\mbox{ years}}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msup>
