^{10^{10^{10^{10^{1.1}}}}}{\mbox{ years}}}"></span></dd></dl></dd></dl></dd=
></dl></dd></dl>
<p>(which corresponds to the scale of an estimated <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Poincar%C3%A9_recurrence_theorem" title=3D"Poincar=C3=A9 r=
ecurrence theorem">Poincar=C3=A9 recurrence time</a> for the quantum state =
of a hypothetical box containing a black hole with the estimated mass of th=
e entire universe, observable or not, assuming a certain <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inflation_(cosmology)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Inflation (cosmology)">inflationary</a> model with an <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inflaton" title=3D"Inflaton">inflaton</a> whose mas=
s is 10<sup>=E2=88=926</sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Planc=
k_mass" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Planck mass">Planck masses</a>), rou=
ghly   10^10^1.288*10^3.884 T  <sup id=3D"cite_ref-page95_9-0" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Large_numbers#cite_note-pa=
ge95-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Large_numbers#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This ti=
me assumes a statistical model subject to Poincar=C3=A9 recurrence. A much =
simplified way of thinking about this time is in a model where the universe=
's history <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Loschmidt%27s_paradox" =
title=3D"Loschmidt's paradox">repeats itself</a> arbitrarily many times due=
 to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ergodic_hypothesis" title=3D"E=
rgodic hypothesis">properties of statistical mechanics</a>; this is the tim=
e scale when it will first be somewhat similar (for a reasonable choice of =
"similar") to its current state again.
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Combinatorial" class=3D"mw-=
redirect" title=3D"Combinatorial">Combinatorial</a> processes give rise to =
astonishingly large numbers. The  <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Factorial" title=3D"Factorial">factorial</a> function, which quantifies <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Permutation" title=3D"Permutation">pe=
rmutations</a> of a fixed set of objects, grows superexponentially as the n=
umber of objects increases.  <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stirl=
ing%27s_formula" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Stirling's formula">Stirlin=
g's formula</a> provides a precise asymptotic expression for this rapid gro=
wth.
</p><p>In statistical mechanics, combinatorial numbers reach such immense m=
agnitudes that they are often expressed using <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Logarithm" title=3D"Logarithm">logarithms</a>.
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/G%C3%B6del_numbers" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"G=C3=B6del numbers">G=C3=B6del numbers</a>, along=
 with similar representations of bit-strings in <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Algorithmic_information_theory" title=3D"Algorithmic informat=
ion theory">algorithmic information theory</a>, are vast=E2=80=94even for m=
athematical statements of moderate length. Remarkably, certain <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pathological_(mathematics)" title=3D"Pathologi=
cal (mathematics)">pathological</a> numbers surpass even the G=C3=B6del num=
bers associated with typical mathematical propositions.
</p><p>Logician <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harvey_Friedman_(m=
athematician)" title=3D"Harvey Friedman (mathematician)">Harvey Friedman</a=
> has made significant contributions to the study of very large numbers, in=
cluding work related to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kruskal%27=
s_tree_theorem" title=3D"Kruskal's tree theorem">Kruskal's tree theorem</a>=
 and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robertson%E2%80%93Seymour=
_theorem" title=3D"Robertson=E2=80=93Seymour theorem">Robertson=E2=80=93Sey=
mour theorem</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"&quot;Billions_and_billions=
&quot;"><span id=3D".22Billions_and_billions.22"></span>"Billions and billi=
ons"</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brack=
et">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLarge_n=
umbers&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: &quot;Bill=
ions and billions&quot;"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection=
-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>To help viewers of <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cosmos:_A=
_Personal_Voyage" title=3D"Cosmos: A Personal Voyage">Cosmos</a></i> distin=
guish between "millions" and "billions", astronomer <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Carl_Sagan" title=3D"Carl Sagan">Carl Sagan</a> stressed =
the "b". Sagan never did, however, say "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Billions_and_billions" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Billions and bi=
llions">billions and billions</a>". The public's association of the phrase =
and Sagan came from a <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Tonig=
ht_Show" title=3D"The Tonight Show">Tonight Show</a></i> skit. Parodying Sa=
gan's effect, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Johnny_Carson" title=
=3D"Johnny Carson">Johnny Carson</a> quipped "billions and billions".<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-11" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Large_numbers#cite_note-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The phrase has, however, now be=
come a humorous fictitious number=E2=80=94the <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Indefinite_and_fictitious_numbers#Sagan's_number" title=3D"Inde=
finite and fictitious numbers">Sagan</a>.  <i>Cf.</i>, <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carl_Sagan#Sagan_units" title=3D"Carl Sagan">Sagan Uni=
t</a>.
</p>
