<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Other_notations">Other nota=
tions</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLarge_=
numbers&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Edit section: Other not=
ations"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span=
></span></div>
<p>Some notations for extremely large numbers:
</p>
<ul><li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Knuth%27s_up-arrow_notatio=
n" title=3D"Knuth's up-arrow notation">Knuth's up-arrow notation</a>, <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperoperator" class=3D"mw-redirect" ti=
tle=3D"Hyperoperator">hyperoperators</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Ackermann_function" title=3D"Ackermann function">Ackermann function=
</a>, including tetration</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conway_chained_arrow_notation"=
 title=3D"Conway chained arrow notation">Conway chained arrow notation</a><=
/li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Steinhaus-Moser_notation" clas=
s=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Steinhaus-Moser notation">Steinhaus-Moser notati=
on</a>; apart from the method of construction of large numbers, this also i=
nvolves a graphical notation with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Polygon" title=3D"Polygon">polygons</a>. Alternative notations, like a more=
 conventional function notation, can also be used with the same functions.<=
/li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fast-growing_hierarchy" title=
=3D"Fast-growing hierarchy">Fast-growing hierarchy</a></li></ul>
<p>These notations are essentially functions of integer variables, which in=
crease very rapidly with those integers. Ever-faster-increasing functions c=
an easily be constructed recursively by applying these functions with large=
 integers as argument.
</p><p>A function with a vertical asymptote is not helpful in defining a ve=
ry large number, although the function increases very rapidly: one has to d=
efine an argument very close to the asymptote, i.e. use a very small number=
, and constructing that is equivalent to constructing a very large number, =
e.g. the reciprocal.
</p>
