og _{10}(\log _{10}(10^{10^{9}}))=3D9}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>Such comparisons of iterated logarithms are common, e.g., in <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_number_theory" title=3D"Analytic num=
ber theory">analytic number theory</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Classes">Classes</h3><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLarge_numbers&amp;acti=
on=3Dedit&amp;section=3D12" title=3D"Edit section: Classes"><span>edit</spa=
n></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>One solution to the problem of comparing large numbers is to define clas=
ses of numbers, such as the system devised by Robert Munafo,<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-14" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Large=
_numbers#cite_note-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> which is based on different "levels" o=
f perception of an average person. Class 0 =E2=80=93 numbers between zero a=
nd six =E2=80=93 is defined to contain numbers that are easily <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Subitizing" title=3D"Subitizing">subitized</a>=
, that is, numbers that show up very frequently in daily life and are almos=
t instantly comparable. Class 1 =E2=80=93 numbers between six and 1,000,000=
=3D10<sup>6</sup> =E2=80=93 is defined to contain numbers whose decimal exp=
ressions are easily subitized, that is, numbers who are easily comparable n=
ot by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cardinality" title=3D"Cardin=
ality">cardinality</a>, but "at a glance" given the decimal expansion.
</p><p>Each class after these are defined in terms of iterating this base-1=
0 exponentiation, to simulate the effect of another "iteration" of human in=
distinguishability. For example, class 5 is defined to include numbers betw=
een 10<sup>10<sup>10<sup>10<sup>6</sup></sup></sup></sup> and 10<sup>10<sup=
>10<sup>10<sup>10<sup>6</sup></sup></sup></sup></sup>, which are numbers wh=
ere <var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">X</var> becomes humanly indistinguis=
hable from <var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">X</var><sup>2</sup> <sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-15" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Large_numbers#cite_note-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> (taking iterated logarithms of s=
uch <var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">X</var> yields indistinguishibility =
firstly between log(<var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">X</var>) and 2log(<v=
ar style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">X</var>), secondly between log(log(<var st=
yle=3D"padding-right: 1px;">X</var>)) and 1+log(log(<var style=3D"padding-r=
ight: 1px;">X</var>)), and finally an extremely long decimal expansion whos=
e length can't be subitized).
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Approximate_arithmetic">App=
roximate arithmetic</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?=
title=3DLarge_numbers&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D13" title=3D"Edit sec=
tion: Approximate arithmetic"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>There are some general rules relating to the usual arithmetic operations=
 performed on very large numbers:
</p>
<ul><li>The sum and the product of two very large numbers are both "approxi=
mately" equal to the larger one.</li>
<li><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D=
"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><mat=
h xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle (1=
0^{a})^{\,\!10^{b}}=3D10^{a10^{b}}=3D10^{10^{b+\log _{10}a}}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <msup>
          <mn>10</mn>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>a</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msup>
        <msup>
          <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mspace width=3D"thinmathspace"></mspace>
            <mspace width=3D"negativethinmathspace"></mspace>
            <msup>
              <mn>10</mn>
              <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <mi>b</mi>
              </mrow>
            </msup>
          </mrow>
        </msup>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <msup>
          <mn>10</mn>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>a</mi>
            <msup>
              <mn>10</mn>
              <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <mi>b</mi>
              </mrow>
            </msup>
          </mrow>
        </msup>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <msup>
          <mn>10</mn>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <msup>
              <mn>10</mn>
              <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <mi>b</mi>
                <mo>+</mo>
                <msub>
                  <mi>log</mi>
                  <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                    <mn>10</mn>
                  </mrow>
                </msub>
                <mo>=E2=81=A1<!-- =E2=81=A1 --></mo>
                <mi>a</mi>
              </mrow>
            </msup>
          </mrow>
        </msup>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle (10^{a})^{\,\=
!10^{b}}=3D10^{a10^{b}}=3D10^{10^{b+\log _{10}a}}}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/a87422c749118b719d7433c67b28a23cc7c9c5dc" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; width:30.097ex; height:3.676ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle (1=
0^{a})^{\,\!10^{b}}=3D10^{a10^{b}}=3D10^{10^{b+\log _{10}a}}}"></span></li>=
</ul>
<p>Hence:
</p>
<ul><li>A very large number raised to a very large power is "approximately"=
 equal to the larger of the following two values: the first value and 10 to=
 the power the second. For example, for very large <span class=3D"mwe-math-=
element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-=
math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org=
/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle n}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
