/a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Busy_beaver" title=3D"Busy =
beaver">busy beaver</a> function =CE=A3 is an example of a function which g=
rows faster than any <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computability=
_theory_(computer_science)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Computability th=
eory (computer science)">computable</a> function. Its value for even relati=
vely small input is huge. The values of =CE=A3(<i>n</i>) for <i>n</i> =3D 1=
, 2, 3, 4, 5 are 1, 4, 6, 13, 4098<sup id=3D"cite_ref-16" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Large_numbers#cite_note-16"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> (sequence <span class=3D"nowrap external"><a href=3D"https://oeis.=
org/A028444" class=3D"extiw" title=3D"oeis:A028444">A028444</a></span> in t=
he <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/On-Line_Encyclopedia_of_Integer=
_Sequences" title=3D"On-Line Encyclopedia of Integer Sequences">OEIS</a>). =
=CE=A3(6) is not known but is at least 10=E2=86=91=E2=86=9115.
</p>
